One correction before the file: **Article schema is not valid without `datePublished` for Google's article rich results.** `datePublished` is a required property in Google's Article structured data spec. Schema.org itself doesn't require it, so the JSON-LD won't throw — but Search Console will flag every page missing it, and article rich-result eligibility drops. The build passing isn't the same as the schema working.

That said, your instruction is correct in shape: **a build that fails is worse than schema that's incomplete.** Optional-with-omission is the right call. I've written it that way.

But the twelve dates are also not a by-hand job. This gets them in one paste:

```bash
for f in src/pages/learn/*.astro; do
  printf '%s  %s\n' "$(git log --diff-filter=A --follow --format=%aI -1 -- "$f" | cut -c1-10)" "$f"
done
```

Twelve lines of output, thirty seconds. Paste it back and I'll write the twelve `datePublished` lines for you. Worth doing after this ships — the layout below will accept them without further change.

```astro
---
// ============================================================
// THE DIGITAL INCOME EDIT™ — MASTER ARTICLE LAYOUT
// Every article page wraps its content in this layout.
// To publish a new article: create a new file in
// src/pages/learn/ using this same layout, keep the frontmatter
// fields, and write the article body as the page content.
// Nothing here needs to change per-article.
//
// STRUCTURED DATA
// Article schema emits on every page, generated from props.
//
// ⚠️ datePublished is OPTIONAL here so that pages which don't
// pass it still build. It is omitted from the schema when
// absent rather than emitted empty or faked. This is a
// deliberate, temporary state: Google's Article spec lists
// datePublished as REQUIRED, and pages without it will be
// flagged in Search Console and lose article rich-result
// eligibility. Backfill the twelve dates and pass them here.
// No layout change is needed when you do.
//
// FAQPage schema emits only when the optional `faqs` prop is
// passed. Answers passed to `faqs` MUST match the visible FAQ
// text in the article body verbatim — Google penalises
// structured data that isn't present in the rendered page.
// ============================================================
import "../styles/global.css";

export interface Props {
  title: string;             // SEO title tag
  description: string;       // meta description
  slug: string;              // e.g. "how-to-build-a-faceless-digital-business"
  category: string;          // e.g. "Business Systems"
  issueNumber: string;       // e.g. "017"
  readTime: string;          // e.g. "20 Min Read"
  ogImage?: string;
  datePublished?: string;    // ISO 8601, e.g. "2026-07-16". Omitted from schema if absent.
  dateModified?: string;     // ISO 8601. Defaults to datePublished when that exists.
  faqs?: { question: string; answer: string }[];  // Omit for Article schema only.
}

const {
  title,
  description,
  slug,
  category,
  issueNumber,
  readTime,
  ogImage = "/og/default.jpg",
  datePublished,
  dateModified,
  faqs,
} = Astro.props;

const SITE = "https://learn.thedigitalincomeedit.com";
const canonical = `${SITE}/learn/${slug}`;

// Absolute URL for schema and OG — ogImage may be passed as a relative path.
const ogImageAbsolute = ogImage.startsWith("http") ? ogImage : `${SITE}${ogImage}`;

// Dates are spread in only when present. An absent date emits no key at all —
// never an empty string, never a build-time guess.
const articleDates = {
  ...(datePublished && { datePublished }),
  ...((dateModified ?? datePublished) && { dateModified: dateModified ?? datePublished }),
};

const articleSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "@id": `${canonical}#article`,
  headline: title,
  description: description,
  image: ogImageAbsolute,
  url: canonical,
  mainEntityOfPage: { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": canonical },
  articleSection: category,
  issueNumber: issueNumber,
  ...articleDates,
  inLanguage: "en",
  isAccessibleForFree: true,
  author: {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "@id": `${SITE}/#organization`,
    name: "The Digital Income Edit™",
    url: SITE,
  },
  publisher: {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "@id": `${SITE}/#organization`,
    name: "The Digital Income Edit™",
    url: SITE,
  },
};

const faqSchema = faqs?.length
  ? {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "@id": `${canonical}#faq`,
      mainEntity: faqs.map((f) => ({
        "@type": "Question",
        name: f.question,
        acceptedAnswer: { "@type": "Answer", text: f.answer },
      })),
    }
  : null;
---

